    "Step 0: Idle",
    "Step 1: Thinking\n  [{ Id = 217ad746-a958-4972-9ae1-f6e099193023\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 4b2d7d80-d5f6-4127-93e6-3cdbf2d6aab6\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 6d7e52d9-2ae0-4c65-8220-f725c89b4ffb))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022To achieve the goal of writing a simple F# function that calculates the factorial of a number using recursion and handling edge cases for 0 and negative numbers, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Define the Function**: Create an F# function named \u0060factorial\u0060 that takes an integer as input.\n2. **Handle Edge Cases**:\n   - If the input is 0, return 1 (since 0! = 1).\n   - If the input is negative, return an error or a special value indicating invalid input.\n3. **Implement Recursion**: Use recursion to calculate the factorial for positive integers.\n\nHere\u0027s the F# code for the \u0060factorial\u0060 function:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet rec factorial n =\n    match n with\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\n    | _ when n \u003C 0 -\u003E failwith \u0022Negative input is not allowed\u0022\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis function uses pattern matching to handle the edge cases and recursion to calculate the factorial for positive integers. If a negative number is passed, it raises an error.\n\nTo validate this function, you can use the \u0060run_tests\u0060 tool to ensure it returns correct values for various inputs, including edge cases.\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 8:15:20 AM\n     Metadata = map [] }]",
